<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Mr J Smith</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt; font-weight:bold">EIS 39</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mineral Products Association (MPA)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Mineral Products Association (MPA) is the trade association for the aggregates, asphalt, cement, concrete, dimension stone, lime, mortar and silica sand industries. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With the recent addition of The British Precast Concrete Federation (BPCF) and the British Association of Reinforcement (BAR), it has a growing membership of 465 companies and is the sectoral voice for mineral products. MPA membership is made up of the vas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t majority of independent SME companies throughout the UK, as well as the 9 major international and global companies. It covers 100% of GB cement production, 90% of aggregates production, 95% of asphalt and ready-mixed concrete production and 70% of precas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t concrete production. Each year the industry supplies £9 billion of materials and services to the £120 billion construction and other sectors. Industry production represents the largest materials flow in the UK economy and is also one of the largest manuf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">acturing sectors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following answers are valid for the UK industries represented by MPA members, where possible and appropriate:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.  What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The usual means of assessing the econo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mic contribution of industries or sectors is through Gross Value Added (GVA). The main problem with such analyses set out in official statistics is that they tend to understate the overall contribution of extractive industries due to the scope of the stand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ard industrial classifications used. For extractive industries this means that sectoral GVA will typically not cover value added or downstream activities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 2012 MPA commissioned Capital Economics</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to evaluate the economic contribution of the industries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and companies represented by MPA. This scope covered mineral extraction and processing but also the manufacture of mineral products such as cement, concrete and asphalt and associated activities such as industry transport. Outcomes of the research included</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Industry turnover of £9 billion pa</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sector GVA of over £4 billon pa</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tax payments of over £1 billion pa</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Labour productivity nearly 2.5 times the national average</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Annual expenditure of £5.2 billion pa on suppliers, of which £3.5 billion is on suppliers in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Industries supplied by the industry have a turnover of £400 billion pa</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.  How do the UK-based extractive industries support employment a) in the UK and b) for UK citizens overseas?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are two distinct elements to this question: direct </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">employment and indirect employment.  The Capital Economics research defined direct employment as those engaged in extraction, the production of mineral products and associated activities and estimated direct employment in 2011 at between 33,000 and 39,000.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The research also estimated that 37,200 jobs in the industry supply chain were supported by the mineral products industry within the scope of MPA membership. The direct employment of the industry is distributed throughout the UK and is predominantly rural</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> based. There are particular concentrations of direct employment in The East Midlands, South West and Yorkshire and Humberside regions of England and in Scotland. Supply chain or indirect employment is also distributed nationally, with significant employme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nt in the North West, East and West Midlands and South East of England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(b) There is no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> direct knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the UK indigenous extractive minerals industries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’ support for UK citizens overseas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.  Does UK industry benefit more widely from the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">position as a centre for extractive industries e.g. in sales of machinery and services to international businesses in the sector?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Being modern industries the UK extractive minerals industries are customers for a huge number of manufactured products, rangi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng from ICT equipment at one end of the scale, to heavy mobile or static plant at the other end</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (Including marine aggregate dredgers at £35 million)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Some of this will be indigenously produced – a classic example might be JCB equipment and plant – but muc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h will not, albeit some plant and equipment will be franchised to UK manufacturers that are owned overseas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> much of the repair and maintenance work will be carried out by UK operators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Traditionally, the UK has been a manufacturer of such plant and eq</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uipment, possibly stemming from the fact that much of the high end technical training and education has been done at the Royal School of Mines or its Cornish counterpart, the Camborne School of Mines, and other British Universities, generating a long stand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing relationship with things British!  In the global current market, however, it is doubted whether the UK supporting industries benefit from either traditional empathy or training experience, other than in consultancy work such as law, design, environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">al management, health and safety or general management.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.  Has the boom in London-listed extractive companies with businesses overseas over the last two decades resulted in a strengthening in the UK’s competitive position in this sector?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is not s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">omething on which MPA can comment directly, as its responsibilities lie solely with UK operations, albeit with an additional interest in European Commission and Parliamentary activities, where they have the potential to influence the way the industries in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK operate.  In percentage terms the tonnages of UK extracted (non-energy) minerals and downstream products owned by overseas listed companies is about 75%, the remainder (UK owned, but not necessarily listed) being solely involved in UK based operatio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ns.  It should be noted in this context that the level of regulation, the high cost of energy and difficulties in establishing reserves with planning consents (replenishing land banks) has the potential to divert future investment in the UK to more profita</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ble operations overseas, thus endangering the resource security of essential minerals for the UK market.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.  What are the corporate governance concerns raised by the number of extractive industries companies listed in the UK? Are there reputational risks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">for the UK and UK financial institutions in being a centre for such businesses?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We would point out that the Mineral Products industry in the UK operates in a regulated environment and exhibits high standards of sustainability performance.  For a number of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> years the MPA has published Sustainable Development reports indicating:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">High proportions of industry operations with certified environmental and quality management systems</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Significant liaison with local communities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">High proportion of sales of products </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">certified as  Responsibly Sourced</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Significant and growing contribution to nature conservation and biodiversity through the operation and restoration of industry sites.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.  Is there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive industries and NGOs?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The relationship between the extractive minerals industries in the UK and the NGOs has been transformed over the past decade or so, such that the joint work and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> initiatives being carried out in the UK are now signalled as exemplars worldwide.    It is on record, for example, that Natural England, as the English environmental policy advisor to Government, has stated that the MPA members have the ability, with care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fully managed operations and subsequent site restoration, to satisfy 100% of nine out of 11 UK Biodiversity Action Plan targets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on their own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Further, NE has said that the UK extractive minerals industries “are uniquely placed…..” to enhance biodiversity in the country and, in tandem with the RSPB and the industries, has created an initiative called “Nature after Minerals”, which has as its b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">asis the desire to ensure that extractive operations and restoration make the most beneficial contribution to UK biodiversity over the long term. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There has been a particularly productive relationship developed between the UK’s marine </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aggregate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dredging i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ndustry, regulators, agencies and NGOs which has resulted in a greater understanding of the marine environment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One factor in the closer relationship between the UK mineral products industry and NGOs was the availability of funding from the UK aggregates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">levy through the operation of the Aggregates Levy Sustainability Fund (ALSF). The ALSF was set up when the aggregates levy was introduced in 2002 to direct a proportion of levy revenues into initiatives to minimise environmental impacts and support local c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ommunity initiatives. Over a number of years about 6% of aggregates levy funding was used for ALSF purposes. Although independent research identified significant benefits and value for money arising from the ALSF, the scheme was scrapped by Government in E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ngland in 2011 and the only part of the UK in which the schemes continues is Wales. The marine aggregates ALSF programme was described recently by the body representing industry, regulator, agency and NGO interests as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“one of the most substantial investmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ts in UK marine research </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that has taken place this decade</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the outputs from this programme have delivered significant added value in supporting the UK Government’s wider objectives for sustainable marine management, particularly the development of mari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ne planning.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This very effective mechanism to encourage positive and productive projects and initiatives involving industry, NGOs and other interested parties could be viewed as a template for co-operative work in the extractive se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ctor elsewhere in the wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rld. MP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A believes that the withdrawal of the ALSF in England n 2011 was a short sighted and damaging decision by Government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The MPA’s Biodiversity and Restoration Awards, to be held in London on 16 October, will amplify these strong relationships and con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tributions developed with NGOs and other organisations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.  Does the UK have the skills base to remain a centre for the extractive industries and to ensure that UK based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such as shale gas?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The experi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ence of the MPA members is that the average age of the workforce has increased to the extent that a high percentage of those (directly) employed is now over 50 years old.  The question remains as to whether there is, or has been sufficient backfilling with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the right numbers and levels of expertise, itself asking a supplementary question about the depth and quality of education and training available, as much as a wider one on the image of the extractive industries and their attractiveness to newer generatio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ns!  The requisite skills base is probably in place, but whether is being directed accurately to fulfil the future further demands of the extractive minerals industries is less certain. Further, with the reduction or closure of certain types of extraction </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">industry, notably underground mining, in the UK there are fewer sites where trainees can learn their trade by practical, hands on site training in this country, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which has reduced still further the ability to provide high quality experts in relevant fields.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The mineral products industry is now working closely with the University of Derby to support the establishment and development of the University as a centre of excellence for extractive industry education. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8.  What is the impact of the industry of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UK signing up to the EITI?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government decision to sign up to the EITI initiative was taken without consultation with the largest element of the extractive industry in the UK, represented by the MPA. British Geological Survey identifies UK mineral prod</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uction as follows:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Total UK mineral extraction of c. 300 million tonnes</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Of which, aggregates minerals produced by our industry account for 170 million tonnes</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Of which, oil and gas production , offshore and on shore, was 85 million tonnes</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Of which, coal pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oduction was 16 million tonnes.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Given the scale of aggregates related mineral extraction in the UK we are surprised that there has been no substantive consultation or discussion with the UK minerals product industry to date.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The EITI requires significant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reporting and verification of data from extractive industries operating in the UK but we have yet to receive clarity about the implications for UK operators.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9.  Would increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition fro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">m elsewhere or can it be used to make the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The question is not so much about the regulation of the listed companies, but the regulation of the industries’ activities: the two are quite d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ifferent issues.  MPA cannot comment on the former, but can comment on the latter! </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In this case it can be argued that the UK extractive minerals industries are already amongst the most heavily regulated industries in both the country and, probably, inte</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rnationally.  An MPA assessment in 2012 identified 228 laws and regulations related to planning and environmental matters requiring management by the mineral products industry.  There will be some items of legislation or regulation that seem misdirected or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> superfluous, but one thing is absolutely clear: the industry does not need any more regulation.  In terms of the UK being a centre of best practice on the world stage, there is no doubt that that is the case for the operations of the extraction processes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and all that goes therewith.  MPA cannot comment on whether this applies equally to corporate governance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">10. What is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">for them?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The ownership of the UK extractive minerals industries has changed significantly over the past two decades.  20 years ago, ownership of the industries was almost exclusively in UK listed or private company hands.  However, within the MPA areas o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f responsibility some 75% of extractive production, by volume and value, is now owned by international companies not based in the UK or listed in London.   The ownership of larger private and public SMEs operating in the UK is both UK and overseas based an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d the 300 plus smaller SMEs operating in the UK are very largely private UK – owned businesses. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Additional information:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The mineral products industry’s contribution to the UK: </span><a href="http://www.mineralproducts.org/documents/MPA_MTL_Document.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">h</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">ttp://www.mineralproducts.org/documents/MPA_MTL_Document.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Capital Economics Report: New Research Highlights Critical Economic Role of the Mineral Products Industry:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.mineralproducts.org/feature_ce_report.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.minera</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">lproducts.org/feature_ce_report.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The mineral products industry—key facts at a glance:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.mineralproducts.org/documents/Mineral_Products_Industry_at_a_Glance.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.mineralproducts.org/documents/Mineral_Products_Industry_at_a_Glance.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.mineralproducts.org/featu